               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1357" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1357" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1357" type="surname" value="COX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1357" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE COX</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Henry Cox, a shoemaker, and live in the City-road. The prisoner occupied a furnished room in our house. On Saturday, the 21st of August, he did not come home at night, and on Sunday morning I missed three pairs of boots, which had been safe in the shop as late as half-past twelve on Saturday night—about three the next afternoon I went up to the prisoner's bed-room, and to my great sur<lb></lb>prise I found him there—I asked him how he came there—he told me not to be alarmed, that he had got over the Lying-in-Hospital wall, and in at the back parlour window—he went out—I went up to his room, and saw the string of these boots part of the way out of his portmanteau, which stood under the window—I told my husband—he got a policeman—in the even<lb></lb>ing the prisoner came home, and was accused of it—he said he was guilty, and he meant to return them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAMBERS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are these the boots? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes— they are torn by the lace-holes—they have been tried on some one—we rather think the prisoner had a female into the house—he could get one in by opening the door when he was in the house—I think some female must have had these on—no man could have got them on—the prisoner said he was drunk—I said, "I have a charge to make about a pair of drab boots I have missed"—he said, "I know I have taken them, they are in my port<lb></lb>manteau"—he gave the policeman the key, and the boots were there—he had been at home nine or ten weeks—he gets drunk most abominably, and then he is the most troublesome fellow that ever came into a house.</p>
               <p>
